The rector of Kaduna Polytechnic, Prof. Idris Mohammed Bugaje, has said that scrapping Almajiri Islamic education system in the North would be a difficult task to accomplish. Bugaje stated this in his opening remark at the closing ceremony of a capacity building workshop for technical and vocational teachers from Katsina State on enhancing the trade skills in vocational educational institutes in Kaduna State. He stressed that “scrapping almajiri system is impossible and therefore can only be upgraded so that the affected youths and operators can be empowered with skills.” The rector also said that begging is a bad thing “it can be removed,  instead of learning only religious knowledge, add skills to the curriculum so that students from Almajiri schools will come out learned and be able to do some skills”. Prof. Bugaje noted that almajiri system has been in existence for over 950 years, saying that empowering them and Nigerians with skills is another way to tackle insecurity bedevilling the country. “We should empower people to be job creators and not job seekers, technical education change the fortune of a country” he said. He commended the Katsina State Governor, Rt. Hon. Aminu Bello Masari for the wonderful opportunity given to citizens of the State while further urging him to invest more in the education sector. Speaking with newsmen shortly after the closing ceremony, the training manger, Aminu Nasir Jasawa disclosed that 40 technical and vocational teachers participated in the one week workshop exercise, and urged the participants to make good use of the opportunity given to them. Jasawa noted that the workshop was organized by Kinetic Consult Limited in partnership with Kaduna polytechnic.  